[This is the most detailed report to data regarding this large
outbreak and was likely prepared prior to the report of several more
deaths in Germany and a link to Spanish cucumbers. Additionally, it
appears that all the EU cases outside of the German borders, to this
point, are related to individuals who acquired the unusual _E. coli_
isolate in Germany prior to travel.

The antimicrobial resistance pattern of this isolate is also quite
unusual. This could reflect the use of antimicrobial agents in the
feed of the original host animals. It should be stated, however, that
antimicrobials should be not be empirically used in VTEC infections
since the use increases the risk for HUS. It is not stated if
antimicrobial use was a factor in the prominent risk of HUS in this
outbreak.

The absence of intimin-production in the isolate is also uncommon as
the protein is an adherence factor important in virulence. The eae
designation stands for _E. coli_ attaching and effacing. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] News report
Date: Fri 27 May 2011
Source: Deutsche Welle, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [edited]
http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,,15110995,00.html


The _E. coli_ outbreak in Germany is spreading, with several new
cases reported on Fri 27 May 2011. Consumers are still being advised
to exercise caution with raw vegetables.

The German institute responsible for disease control and prevention
has reported 60 new cases of severe infection with the _E. coli_
bacterium.

The director of the Robert Koch Institute (RKI), Reinhard Burger,
told the news show "Morgenmagazin" on ARD television that the patients
were suffering from hemolytic uremic syndrome (HUS).

On Thu 26 May 2011, the Hamburg Institute for Hygiene identified
cucumbers from Spain as the source of the outbreak. The Spanish health
ministry has launched an investigation. Officials said authorities had
contacted 2 farms in the provinces of Malaga and Almeria, where the
cucumbers are believed to have come from.

However, the ministry also said a contamination within Germany itself
could not be ruled out. This possibility was also mentioned by the
managing director of one of the farms, who claimed that a load of
cucumbers fell on the ground on the way to the Hamburg wholesale
market.

The RKI says that the current _E. coli_ outbreak is the worst ever on
record in Germany, with more people infected in a week than otherwise
in an entire year.

[Byline: Timothy Jones]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

******
[3] European Commission report
Date: Thu 26 May 2011
Source: Agence France-Presse (AFP) [edited]
http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iElyG_DjhfgRA9Yk77l8mjo11yuA?docId=CNG.3ae2c53954517f8b64ed19d65a6b92c0.d91


Cucumbers from Spain have been confirmed as one of the sources
responsible for an outbreak in Germany of _E. coli_ [O140], a
potentially lethal food borne bacteria, the European Commission said
Thu 26 May 2011.

The EU executive said it had notified the 27 members of the European
Union "about one of the confirmed sources responsible" for the
outbreak, principally in Germany where it is blamed for 2 deaths
[other reports have put the death toll at 3 or 4 - Mod.LL], but also
in Sweden, Denmark, Britain, and the Netherlands.

A commission statement said it had been informed by the German
authorities late Thu 26 May 2011, that they had identified organic
cucumbers from 2 provinces of Spain, Almeria and Malaga, as one of the
sources. A 3rd suspect batch of cucumbers from the Netherlands, but
traded in Germany, was under investigation while German authorities
continue to seek to identify other potential sources.

The commission earlier urged people who recently visited Germany to
watch for symptoms such as bloody diarrhea. "People who have recently
visited Germany should pay attention to symptoms, such as bloody
diarrhea, and accordingly consult their physician," said Frederic
Vincent, the commission spokesman for health issues. The commission
stressed that it was "essential" to rapidly identify potential cases
"to prevent the development of severe disease."

The commission said 214 cases of hemolytic-uremic syndrome had been
recorded in Germany, with 68 percent concerning women. Sweden has
reported 10, Denmark 4, Britain 3, and the Netherlands 1.

